The author here exults in the promiscuous slaughter of the German Tribes by each other’s arms, as a brilliant spectacle to Roman eyes—a feeling little congenial to the spirit of Christianity, but necessarily nurtured by the gladiatorial shows and bloody amusements of the Romans, to say nothing of the habitual hostility which they waged against all other natione, that did not submit to their dominion.
